    "recap_headline": "Wake Forest Athletics",
    "recap_text": "WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. \u2013\nDespite a career day by junior centerfielder\nJavar Williams\n, the No. 12 Wake Forest baseball team (15-5, 3-3 ACC) dropped the series finale against No. 20 Florida State (16-3, 3-0 ACC) by a score of 12-6 on Sunday afternoon at David F. Couch Ballpark.\nWilliams recorded career highs in hits, RBIs and home runs as he ended the game going 4-for-5 with two home runs and four RBIs.\nThe Dartmouth, Mass., native opened the scoring with a solo home run over the left field wall in the first inning, before adding a two-run blast in the seventh. Williams also added an RBI single with the bases loaded in the bottom of the eighth.\nSophomore catcher\nMatt Conte\ntallied a pair of hits against the Seminoles, including a solo home run in the ninth.\nSophomore right-hander\nTroy Dressler\nimpressed on the mound as he struck out a career-high eight batters while allowing just one run in 4.0 innings of relief.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nFlorida State grabbed a 2-0 lead in the top of the first.\nJunior centerfielder\nJavar Williams\ncut the deficit in half in the bottom of the first as he lasered a solo shot over the left field wall.\nThe Seminoles tacked on a pair of runs in the second to extend their lead.\nFlorida State added another run in the third.\nThe Seminoles pushed their lead to 8-1 in the fourth.\nSophomore reliever\nTroy Dressler\ntallied a pair of strikeouts in a scoreless fifth inning.\nThe Mifflinburg, Pa., native continued to deal on the mound as he struck out the side in the sixth.\nWake Forest threatened with the bases loaded in the bottom of the sixth, but were unable to capitalize.\nThe Deacs logged another three-up, three-down frame in the top of the seventh.\nFollowing a leadoff single by freshman shortstop\nJD Stein\n, Williams rocketed his second home run of the game to make it 8-3 in the home half of the seventh.\nFlorida State scored four runs in the top of the eighth.\nWilliams tallied his career-high fourth RBI of the afternoon on an RBI single in the bottom of the eighth.\nJunior first baseman\nKade Lewis\nadded a sacrifice fly to make it 12-5.\nSenior right-hander\nWill Ray\npitched a scoreless frame in the ninth.\nSophomore catcher\nMatt Conte\nlaunched a solo home run to left-center to move the Deacs within six runs in the bottom of the ninth.\nWake Forest fell to Florida State, 12-6.\nFROM COACH WALTER\n\"It's tough to play from behind like we did all weekend against a good team. We had some chances to grab some momentum after Javar [Williams] home run in the first inning. We got two outs on three pitches and had the 9-hole hitter on a 0-2 count. We walked him and then made a bad 2-2 pitch on the next hitter for the home run and the momentum swung right back into their dugout. We probably should have taken Duncan [Marsten] out after the third inning because he wasn't throwing the ball great. We probably should have gone to Troy [Dressler] a little sooner. That's certainly on me and could have kept it at a 5-1 game and then the other late innings might change. When their starting pitcher was out there with a big lead it makes it easier for him to pitch. We didn't get into their bullpen soon enough. If we would have kept it 5-1, I feel like we could have found a way to win that game. Same thing when we got to 8-3. We needed to put up a zero there. We hit a guy trying to bunt. Then we get a big out and get to 0-2 again to the 9-hole hitter and then he hits a grand slam. We just need to execute better in those situations to grab the momentum. We didn't do that all series. It was a disappointing weekend and now we'll have to be ready to go on Tuesday.\" - Head Coach\nTom Walter\nUP NEXT\nThe Demon Deacons will be back in action at David F. Couch Ballpark for a midweek matchup against Liberty on Tuesday evening. First pitch is scheduled for 6 p.m. and will be streamed live on ACC Network Extra.\nFOLLOW THE DEACS\nGoDeacs.com\n|\nTwitter\n|\nInstagram\n|\nFacebook"
  },
